#import "template.typ": *

#let metadata = (
  title: "Passenger Carrying Endorsement",
  unit: "Passenger Endorsement | Lesson 01",
  author: "C.Moroney",
  version: "v1.0.0",
)

#let lesson = (
title: [Passenger Carrying Endorsement]

,aim: [
To prepare, brief, secure, monitor and manage an informed participant (passenger) while safely operating the aircraft, and to integrate passenger management into normal and emergency procedures.
]


,overview: [
This is a post-certificate endorsement lesson for an existing RPC holder. The lesson is built around the RAAus "Informed Participation" model — the participant (passenger) must be briefed on the nature, limitations and risks of the operation (including amateur-built/LSA considerations where applicable). The lesson is delivered as a single ground briefing followed by one dual flight in which the candidate demonstrates a full passenger brief, secures the "passenger" (the instructor plays the passenger while remaining the safety pilot), and then flies the aircraft and a representative emergency while managing simulated passenger behaviours (anxiety, airsickness, control interference, incapacitation). Eligibility (minimum 10 hours PIC, minimum 2 hours PIC in a two-seat recreational aircraft of the same group/type/design features).
]

,learning_outcomes: [
#text(size:12pt)[*Knowledge*]
- State the eligibility, recency (3 take-offs and 3 landings in the last 90 days in the same Group) and currency requirements for carrying a passenger under the RAAus FOM.
- Explain the Informed Participation model and what a passenger must be told before flight (nature of recreational flight, amateur-built/LSA status if applicable, risks, their freedom to decline).
- Describe the content of a thorough passenger brief: placards, entry/exit, seat adjustment, seatbelt/harness, loose-object and carried-item management, emergency items and egress, and non-interference with controls.
#text(size:12pt)[*Skills*]
- Conduct a complete passenger brief and confirm passenger understanding.
- Correctly seat and secure the passenger; verify harness, door/canopy operation and control clearance.
- Maintain situational awareness and a sterile-cockpit discipline during high-workload phases (take-off, approach, landing) while a passenger is on board.
- Integrate passenger management into a representative emergency (e.g. brief, secure, vital actions, then fly the procedure).
#text(size:12pt)[*Non-Technical Skills*]
- [CRM] Manage the passenger as a potential distraction; assertively call and enforce sterile cockpit when required.
- [TEM] Identify passenger-related threats (anxiety, airsickness, loose items, control interference, medical event) and pre-brief mitigations.
- [SA] Continue an effective lookout and aircraft monitoring while attending to the passenger.
- [HF] Recognise distraction effects and conduct the primary task — fly the aircraft first.
]

,theory_knowledge: [
- RAAus Flight Operations Manual — Passenger Carrying Endorsement (PAX) eligibility, recency and endorsement training requirements.
]

,ground_brief_topics: [
Total time: 30 minutes \
Equipment required: \

*Non-Technical Skills* (5 minutes)
- [CRM] Sterile cockpit — when and how to enforce it with a passenger on board.
- [TEM] Passenger as a threat source: anxiety, airsickness, loose items, control interference, incapacitation.
- [HF] Distraction management — aviate, navigate, communicate, *then* attend to the passenger.
- [SA] Maintaining lookout and monitoring while talking to a passenger.

*Legal and Informed Participation* (5 minutes)
- PAX eligibility and recency requirements from the FOM.
- The Informed Participation model: what the participant (passenger) must be told and acknowledge before flight.
- Private cost sharing limitations and the prohibition on profit.

*The Passenger Brief* (15 minutes)
- Pre-boarding: placards, entry/exit, danger areas (prop), loose objects and carried items.
- In the seat: adjustment, seatbelt/harness fitting and operation, door/canopy operation, emergency egress, emergency items.
- Non-interference with controls.
- Managing well being — comfort, temperature, motion sickness prevention, what to expect.

*Operating with a Passenger* (5 minutes)
- Re-run weight and balance and performance for the loaded condition; note revised speeds, longer ground roll, reduced climb.
- Changed handling and trim; smoother inputs for comfort.
- Integrating passenger briefing and management into the emergency plan and vital actions.
]

,ground_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Instructor*]
- Confirm candidate eligibility (PIC hours, 2 hrs RAAus, same type/design) and recency before flight.
- Brief the role-play: instructor will act as an anxious/airsick/interfering/incapacitated passenger at set points while remaining safety pilot.
- Pre-select an emergency-landing area and confirm the simulated emergency to be flown.
#text(size:12pt)[*Student*]
- Confirm own recency and currency; complete IMSAFE.
- Deliver a full passenger brief to the instructor (as passenger) and confirm understanding before boarding.
- Seat and secure the passenger; verify harness, door/canopy and control clearance.
]

,in_flight_tasks:[
#text(size:12pt)[*Demonstration*]
- Not applicable. Instructor plays passenger while continuing to be safety pilot.
- Instructor introduces realistic passenger scenarios: sick; distracting; speaking over radio calls; resting on interfering with controls.

#text(size:12pt)[*Student Practice*]
- Operate the aircraft accurately: In flight manoeuvres within tolerances (heading ±10°, altitude ±150 ft, balance ±¼ ball) while interacting with the passenger.
- Respond to simulated passenger scenarios introduced by the instructor: nervous/anxious passenger, airsickness onset, passenger reaching for controls, distracting passenger.
- Conduct a simulated emergency (e.g. FLWOP) with the passenger on board: give the emergency passenger brief, confirm secured, complete vital actions, then fly the procedure while keeping the passenger managed.
- Enforce sterile cockpit on take-off, approach and landing.
]

,common_errors:[
- *Letting the passenger be distracting*: Enforce sterile cockpit; aviate first, converse second.
- *Fixating on the passenger during an emergency*: Fly the aircraft first; manage the passenger within the procedure, not instead of it.
- *Failing to notice air-sickness symptoms"*: Notice the symptoms and intervene early. Avoid control inputs that will aggravate the condition.
]

,post_flight:[
- *Student Self-Assessment* (5 min): Candidate reviews brief quality, sterile-cockpit discipline and how passenger management affected workload.
- *Instructor Feedback* (10 min):
  - Evaluate against completion standards (S, C, NC).
- *Scenario Reflection* (5 min): "Your passenger becomes airsick on late downwind — how does that change your approach and landing plan?"
- *Next Steps*:
]

,standards_for_progression:[
- *Passenger brief*: Complete and structured; covers Informed Participation, placards, entry/exit, harness, egress, loose items, non-interference with controls or communication, with understanding confirmed (C).
- *Seat and secure*: passenger correctly secured; harness, door/canopy and control clearance verified (C).
- *Aircraft operation*: Maintains normal Pilot Certificate tolerances; smooth inputs for passenger comfort (C).
- *Passenger management*: Manages anxiety, airsickness, control interference and incapacitation scenarios without loss of aircraft control (C).
- *Emergency integration*: Briefs and secures passenger, completes vital actions, and flies the procedure with the passenger managed (C).
- *Legal*: Correctly explains Informed Participation, recency and cost-sharing limitations (C).
- *Outcome*: Recorded in the training record (S/C/NC) with comments.
]

,safety:[
- *Weather*: Conditions suitable for dual flight — light winds and smooth air preferred so passenger-management scenarios can be run without excess workload; horizon visible, ceiling > 2500 ft AGL.
- *Altitude*: Conduct simulated incapacitation/emergency scenarios at a safe height.
- *Emergency Procedures*: Forced-landing area pre-selected; brief that the instructor remains the safety pilot and will take control with "I have control" at any point.
- *TEM*:
  - The instructor's role-play must never compromise the real safety of the flight.
  - Control-interference simulation is conducted gently and at a safe height; instructor is ready to take control instantly.
  - Maintain lookout and traffic awareness, especially in the training area and circuit.
]

,homework:[
- Read the current RAAus FOM section covering the Passenger Carrying Endorsement 
- Re-read the Bob Tait BAK sections on weight and balance and on take-off/landing performance for the loaded condition.
- Prepare a written passenger brief checklist for the candidate's own aircraft type (if applicable)
- Consider: "If a passenger with reduced mobility wants to fly with me, what extra items in the briefing will I need to consider? Is the increased risk acceptable? Do they need to be made aware of the increased risk in order to be an informed participant?"
]
)

#show: body => lesson_plan(metadata, lesson, body)
